'''Fartun Abukar Omar''' (born August 3, 1986<ref>https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ab/fartun-abukar-omar-1.html</ref>) is a [[Somalia|Somali]] [[Athletics (sport)|athlete]].

==Biography==
She [[Somalia at the 2004 Summer Olympics|represented Somalia]] at the [[2004 Summer Olympics]] in [[Athens]], despite her country having been without a government for thirteen years at that time. She took part in the [[Athletics at the 2004 Summer Olympics – Women's 100 metres|women's 100 metres race]], and finished last in her heat, nonetheless achieving a personal best of 14.29 seconds.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sportacademy/hi/fun/photos/newsid_3605000/3605216.stm# "Meet the Olympics' unsung heroes"], BBC</ref> She was 18 at the time of the event.<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=950CEED6163EF932A1575BC0A9629C8B63 "SUMMER 2004 GAMES; Free at Last, Islamic Women Compete With Abandon"], ''New York Times'', August 21, 2004</ref> She had never before run a competition on a track, and drifted into the wrong lane for part of the race.<ref>[http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/sport/article132295.ece "More Olympics news"], ''The Sun'', August 21, 2004</ref> [[ESPN]] noted that she was the first [[Islam|Muslim]] woman ever to represent Somalia at any [[Olympic Games]].<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/news/story?id=1887619 "The passion of the athlete"], ESPN, September 25, 2004</ref>

