{{Infobox NCAA football school | CurrentSeason = 2015 Nihon Phoenix football team | TeamName = Nihon Phoenix football | Image = NihonPhoenix.jpg | ImageSize = 100 | HeadCoach = 橋詰功(Isao Hashizume) | HeadCoachYear =2018- | HCWins = | HCLosses = | Stadium = | StadiumLink = | StadCapacity = | StadSurface = | Location = [[Tokyo, Japan]] | Conference = [[Kantoh Collegiate American Football Association]] | ConfDivision = Division 1 (Top 8) | FirstYear = {{Start date|1940}} | AthleticDirector = | WebsiteName = NihonPhoenix.com | WebsiteURL = http://nu-phoenix.com/ | ATWins = | ATLosses = | ATTies = | ATPercentage = | BowlWins = | BowlLosses = | BowlTies = | NatlTitles = 4 | ConfTitles = 20 | DivTitles = | AllAmericans = | uniform = | Color1 = Red | Color1Hex = FF0000 | Color2 = White | Color2Hex = FFFFFF | Outfitters = | FightSong = | MascotDisplay = | MarchingBand = | PagFreeLabel = | PagFreeValue = }}
The '''Nihon Phoenix football''' program, established in 1940, represents [[Nihon University]] in [[college football]]. Nihon is a member of the [[Kantoh Collegiate American Football Association]]. Nihon Phoenix football has been a powerhouse in Japan's college football along with the [[Kwansei Gakuin Fighters football|Kwansei Gakuin University Fighters]] for four decades.<ref name="NHK20180516">{{cite web|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/nhknewsline/backstories/angerspreads/ |title=Anger Spreads after College Football Violence |publisher=Nippon Hoso Kyokai | date=2018-05-16 |accessdate=2018-06-20 }}</ref>
== Features == Nihon won the Japanese collegiate championships for 17 times including 5 in a row when Mikio Shinokake was the team's head coach. Shinokake adopted the shotgun formation as the team's basic offensive formation. He often had played the team's best athlete as a quarterback in the formation, and the qb played the dual role of qb and tailback. The strategy had worked very well because the size and the power of Japanese defenders had not been so big nor strong enough to injury the qb, making the defenders confused whether the qb throws the ball or keeps the ball for qb draw. Nihon sometimes used the Dragonfly formation which is a kind of the shotgun formation, and two quarterbacks are aligned at the same time in the formation. These qb's also play the dual role of qb and tailback, then it is almost the same as if four players were aligned in the backfield. Nihon scored two touchdowns using the formation against the [[College of William & Mary]] at the [[Ivy Bowl]] in 1993.
== Controversy == The Nihon University Phoenix has played friendly exhibition games against the [[Kwansei Gakuin Fighters football|Kwansei Gakuin University Fighters]] for forty years, and during an exhibition match on May 6, 2018, a defensive player of Phoenix tackled a quarterback of Fighters from behind at least two seconds after throwing an incomplete-pass.<ref name="JT20180515">{{cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2018/05/15/more-sports/football/dangerous-plays-nihon-university-defender-rock-college-football/ |title=Dangerous plays by Nihon University defender rock college football |access-date=May 21, 2018}}</ref><ref name="Mainichi20180516">{{cite web|url=https://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20180516/p2a/00m/0na/019000c |title=Dangerous illegal tackle of university quarterback ordered by head coach: sources |access-date=May 21, 2018}}</ref> The quarterback was forced to leave the game.<ref name="Mainichi20180516" /> Also, the defender committed three fouls in the match.<ref name="JT20180515" /> However, he was in tears at the bench after substituted off.<ref name="Mainichi20180516" /> Just after the match, the Phoenix head coach commented on the defender's plays as if he approved of the fouls or encouraged the players to commit them.<ref name="JT20180515" /> This dangerous illegal late-hit and the coach's comment stirred a national controversy.<ref name="JT20180515" /><ref name="Mainichi20180516" /><ref name="NBC20180519">{{cite web|url=https://collegefootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2018/05/19/japanese-college-football-coach-resigns-over-controversial-hit/ |title=Japanese college football coach resigns over controversial hit |access-date=May 21, 2018}}</ref>
Ex-[[NFL]] line-backer [[Masafumi Kawaguchi]] pointed out that he'd never seen anything like the late-hit that became a problem.<ref name="Mainichi20180516" /> The Kwansei Gakuin University formally protested to the Nihon University,<ref name="Mainichi20180516" /> and accused Nihon of intentionally trying to hurt the quarterback.<ref name="NBC20180519" /> [[Daichi Suzuki]], the chief of the government's [[Ministry of Education, Culture, Sports, Science and Technology|Japan Sports Agency]], launched an inquiry and called the play into question.<ref name="JT20180519">{{cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2018/05/19/more-sports/football/nihon-university-coach-masato-uchida-apologizes-controversial-play-quits/ |title=Nihon University coach Masato Uchida quits over controversial play |access-date=May 21, 2018}}</ref>
The quarterback was damaged in his [[Vertebral column|spine]].<ref name="NBC20180519" /> The defender who injured him was obviously ordered to make dirty tackles by Nihon Phoenix coaches,<ref name="NT20180522" /> and later admitted it in public according to his conscience.<ref name="JT20180522">{{cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2018/05/22/more-sports/football/nichidais-taisuke-miyagawa-says-coach-ordered-dirty-hits-football-game/ |title=Nihon University player Taisuke Miyagawa says coach ordered dirty tackles |publisher=Japan Times |date=2018-05-22 |accessdate=2018-06-20}}</ref> The head coach of Nihon, nevertheless, denied that he had ordered his players to play dirty and resigned as coach without giving veracity in explain.<ref name="JT20180519" /><ref name="JT20180524">{{cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2018/05/24/general/veracity-lacking-explanation-coaches/ |title=Veracity lacking in explanation by coaches |publisher=Japan Times |date=2018-05-24 |accessdate=2018-06-20}}</ref> Anger spread in nation-wide.<ref name="NHK20180516" />
Reporters of ''[[New York Times]]'' speculated that this controversy related to deep-rooted cultural dynamics including what the Japanese call “[[power harassment|power hara]]”.<ref name="NT20180522">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/22/sports/football/japanese-football.html |title=The Football Hit Felt All Over Japan |publisher=New York Times |date=2018-05-22 |accessdate=2018-06-20}}</ref>
